We’re using the package “FactoMineR”

There’s another package called ADE4 but it is harder to use

You’d better use ADE4 only for advanced techniques

We’ll go through the tutorial produced by M. Husson to demo FactoMineR

install.packages("FactoMineR")
library(FactoMineR)

MCA uses qualitative (Factor) Variables

Computing the Multiple Correspondance Analysis

res.mca = MCA(df, quanti.sup=19, quali.sup=c(20:36))

Plotting the results

Variables + Quali Sup are invisible

plot.MCA(res.mca, invisible=c("var","quali.sup"), cex=0.7)

Individuals + Quali SUP are invisible

plot.MCA(res.mca, invisible=c("ind","quali.sup"), cex=0.7)

Individuals are invisible

plot.MCA(res.mca, invisible=c("ind"))

Individuals and variables are invisible

plot.MCA(res.mca, invisible=c("ind", "var"))

#tea: the data set used
#quanti.sup: vector of indexes of continuous supplementary variables
#quali.sup: vector of indexes of categorical supplementary variables
#invisible: the elements not to be plotted
#cex: character size

Computing the PCA

res.pca = PCA(decathlon[,1:10], scale.unit=TRUE, ncp=5, graph=T)

#decathlon: the data set used
#scale.unit: to choose whether to scale the data or not 
#ncp: number of dimensions kept in the result
#graph: to choose whether to plot the graphs or no

Displaying supplementary variables

res.pca = PCA(decathlon[,1:12], scale.unit=TRUE, ncp=5, quanti.sup=c(11: 12), graph=T)

#decathlon: the data set used
#scale.unit: to choose whether to scale the datas or not
#ncp: number of dimensions kept in the result
#quanti.sup: vector of the indexes of the quantitative supplementary variables
#graph: to choose whether to plot the graphs or not

Adding a qualitative supplementary variable

res.pca = PCA(decathlon, scale.unit=TRUE, ncp=5, quanti.sup=c(11: 12), quali.sup=13, graph=T)

#decathlon: the data set used
#scale.unit: to choose whether to scale the datas or not
#ncp: number of dimensions kept in the result
#quanti.sup: vector of the indexes of the quantitative supplementary variables
#quali.sup: vector of the indexes of the qualitative supplementary variables
#graph: to choose whether to plot the graphs or not

Plotting the individuals cloud

plot.PCA(res.pca, axes=c(1, 2), choix="ind", habillage=13)

#res.pca: the result of a PCA
#axes: the axes to plot
#choix: the graph to plot ("ind" for the individuals, "var" for the variables)
#habillage: to choose the colours of the individuals: no colour ("none"), a colour for each individual ("ind") or to colour the individuals according to a categorical variable (give the number of the qualitative variable)

Plotting the variables cloud

plot.PCA(res.pca, axes=c(1, 2), choix="var", habillage=13)
